SUMMARY:Marharyta Zhurunova and Bohdan Lokatyr | Land Art in Ukraine: Wha
 t It Is and Where to Find It
DESCRIPTION:Speaking from the perspective of practitioners rather than a 
 theorists\, Marharyta Zhurunova and Bohdan Lokatyr will talk about how th
 is artistic practice appeared in the Ukrainian context\, how it evolved o
 ver time\, and why it continues to exist today. The talk will also explor
 e the different forms land art has taken and why it has effectively becom
 e an umbrella term that encompasses many other meanings and practices.  A
 long the way the artists will address several questions: Who are the seas
 onal land artists? Who is being pursued by the terra-police? How can fog 
 be preserved\, and is it possible to move a landscape?  The artistic coll
 aborators will present another public lecture (https://eskenazi.indiana.e
 du/events/speaker-series/mckinney-series/upcoming-events/2026-04-17-zhuru
 nova-lokatyr.html) Friday\, April 17 about their own land art projects an
 d recent site-specific and environmental works shaped by the realities of
  war in Ukraine.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p data-olk-copy-source="MessageBody">  Spea
 king from the perspective of practitioners rather than a theorists\, Marh
 aryta Zhurunova and Bohdan Lokatyr will talk about how this artistic prac
 tice appeared in the Ukrainian context\, how it evolved over time\, and w
 hy it continues to exist today. The talk will also explore the different 
 forms land art has taken and why it has effectively become an umbrella te
 rm that encompasses many other meanings and practices.</p><p>  Along the 
 way the artists will address several questions: Who are the seasonal land
  artists? Who is being pursued by the terra-police? How can fog be preser
 ved\, and is it possible to move a landscape?</p><p>  The artistic collab
 orators will present another <a href="https://eskenazi.indiana.edu/events
 /speaker-series/mckinney-series/upcoming-events/2026-04-17-zhurunova-loka
 tyr.html">public lecture</a> Friday\, April 17 about their own land art p
 rojects and recent site-specific and environmental works shaped by the re
 alities of war in Ukraine.</p>
