DTSTART:20260409T200000Z
DTEND:20260409T213000Z
LOCATION:FRANKLIN HALL - Room Number: Media Commons
GEO:39.167025;-86.526406
SUMMARY:Artificial Futures: Critical Visions of AI and Algorithmic Societ
 y: Keynote 1
DESCRIPTION:The keynote "Critical Pedagogy for Artificial Intelligences" 
 by Roc Albalat kicks off the two-day symposium "Artificial Futures\," joi
 ntly presented by the IU Institute for Advanced Study\, Eskenazi Technolo
 gy Innovation Lab\, Luddy Artificial Intelligence Center\, and the Artifi
 cial Intelligence and Digital Futures Initiative offers keynote presentat
 ions by international visiting scholars and panels featuring IU faculty a
 cross disciplines offering "Critical Visions of AI and Algorithmic Societ
 y."  Roc Albalat is a member of Taller Estampa\, an artistic collective o
 f programmers\, filmmakers\, and researchers based in Barcelona. They tak
 e a critical and archaeological approach to audiovisual and digital techn
 ologies\, with a particular focus on archival and experimental media. Sin
 ce 2017\, one of their primary areas of research has been the uses and id
 eologies of artificial intelligence (AI). The collective takes a hands-on
 \, experimental approach to demystify AI\, shifting from abstract theory 
 to a tangible understanding through direct technical engagement. This pre
 sentation will introduce the "Cartography of Generative AI\," a project t
 hat maps the vast\, global ecosystem of actors\, resources\, knowledge\, 
 and infrastructures that underpins the reception of this technology.  Mor
 e information about the symposium is available at Artificial Futures: Cri
 tical Visions of AI &amp\; Algorithmic Society: Upcoming: Special Events:
  Events: Eskenazi School of Art\, Architecture + Design: Indiana Universi
 ty Bloomington (https://eskenazi.indiana.edu/events/special-events/upcomi
 ng/2026-04-10-artificial-futures-symposiumevent.html)
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The keynote <strong>"Critical Pedagogy 
 for Artificial Intelligences"</strong> by Roc Albalat kicks off the two-d
 ay symposium "Artificial Futures\," jointly presented by the IU Institute
  for Advanced Study\, Eskenazi Technology Innovation Lab\, Luddy Artifici
 al Intelligence Center\, and the Artificial Intelligence and Digital Futu
 res Initiative offers keynote presentations by international visiting sch
 olars and panels featuring IU faculty across disciplines offering "Critic
 al Visions of AI and Algorithmic Society."</p><p>  Roc Albalat is a membe
 r of Taller Estampa\, an artistic collective of programmers\, filmmakers\
 , and researchers based in Barcelona. They take a critical and archaeolog
 ical approach to audiovisual and digital technologies\, with a particular
  focus on archival and experimental media. Since 2017\, one of their prim
 ary areas of research has been the uses and ideologies of artificial inte
 lligence (AI). The collective takes a hands-on\, experimental approach to
  demystify AI\, shifting from abstract theory to a tangible understanding
  through direct technical engagement. This presentation will introduce th
 e "Cartography of Generative AI\," a project that maps the vast\, global 
 ecosystem of actors\, resources\, knowledge\, and infrastructures that un
 derpins the reception of this technology.</p><p>  More information about 
 the symposium is available at <a href="https://eskenazi.indiana.edu/event
 s/special-events/upcoming/2026-04-10-artificial-futures-symposiumevent.ht
 ml">Artificial Futures: Critical Visions of AI &amp\; Algorithmic Society
 : Upcoming: Special Events: Events: Eskenazi School of Art\, Architecture
  + Design: Indiana University Bloomington</a></p>
