LOCATION:SIDNEY AND LOIS ESKENAZI MUSEUM OF ART - Room Number: Roehm Fami
 ly Art-making Studio
GEO:39.169144;-86.519739
SUMMARY:Family Art Lab: America 250
DESCRIPTION:Join us this month to celebrate America's 250th Anniversary a
 s we look at American artists and explore the theme "What America Means t
 o Me."  Designed for K-12 students and their families\, this event offers
  a fun and flexible way to spark creativity and connect with each other. 
 All ages and experience levels are welcome!  Come and go at your own pace
 . We recommend planning for at least an hour to explore the gallery and m
 ake art.  Start in the Art Studio inside the Kimberly and John Simpson Ce
 nter for Education on the museum's 2nd floor to pick up your Gallery Chal
 lenge. Then head to the galleries to find the artwork we'll use as inspir
 ation for our project! When you're ready\, head back to the studio for ou
 r hands-on art-making activity that everyone will love.  This program tak
 es place every Second Sunday of the month\, excluding holidays and museum
  closures. Each month features new artworks and materials\, so there's al
 ways something fresh to explore and create!  All children must be chapero
 ned.Know Before You Go:Read about where to find us\, where to park\, acce
 ssibility\, and museum guidelines.Strollers are welcome in the galleries.
  When carrying small children\, please keep them in front of you.  To sav
 e time at the lockers\, avoid bringing backpacks or large bags.  When You
  Arrive:If you parked in the IMU parking lot\, Guest Services can validat
 e your parking voucher for a discount.  Store any large bags in the locke
 rs behind the Guest Services desk.  Head upstairs to the 2nd Floor and in
 to the Simpson Center for Education to start.  When in the galleries\, do
  not touch the artwork. Be mindful to keep body parts and anything you're
  carrying at least 18" away from the art.  Photography is welcome! Just n
 o flash or selfie sticks.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Join us this month to celebrate America
 's 250th Anniversary as we look at American artists and explore the theme
  "What America Means to Me."</p><p>  Designed for K-12 students and their
  families\, this event offers a fun and flexible way to spark creativity 
 and connect with each other. All ages and experience levels are welcome!<
 /p><p>  Come and go at your own pace. We recommend planning for at least 
 an hour to explore the gallery and make art.</p><p>  Start in the Art Stu
 dio inside the Kimberly and John Simpson Center for Education on the muse
 um's 2nd floor to pick up your Gallery Challenge. Then head to the galler
 ies to find the artwork we'll use as inspiration for our project! When yo
 u're ready\, head back to the studio for our hands-on art-making activity
  that everyone will love.</p><p>  This program takes place every Second S
 unday of the month\, excluding holidays and museum closures. Each month f
 eatures new artworks and materials\, so there's always something fresh to
  explore and create!</p><p>  All children must be chaperoned.</p><p><stro
 ng>Know Before You Go:</strong></p><ul><li>Read about <a class="external"
  href="https://artmuseum.indiana.edu/visit/your-visit.html"><span data-co
 ntrast="none">where to find us\, where to park\, accessibility\, and muse
 um guidelines</span></a><span data-contrast="auto">.</span></li><li>Strol
 lers are welcome in the galleries. When carrying small children\, please 
 keep them in front of you.  </li><li>To save time at the lockers\, avoid 
 bringing backpacks or large bags.  </li></ul><p><strong>When You Arrive:<
 /strong></p><ul><li>If you parked in the IMU parking lot\, Guest Services
  can validate your parking voucher for a discount.  </li><li>Store any la
 rge bags in the lockers behind the Guest Services desk.  </li><li>Head up
 stairs to the 2nd Floor and into the Simpson Center for Education to star
 t.  </li><li>When in the galleries\, do not touch the artwork. Be mindful
  to keep body parts and anything you're carrying at least 18" away from t
 he art.  </li><li>Photography is welcome! Just no flash or selfie sticks.
   </li></ul>
